from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def train_test(df,stratify):
    if df.shape[0]<600:
        size=0.45
    else:
        size=0.33
    y=df.iloc[:,-1]
    x=df.drop(columns=[y.name])
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=size, random_state=0, stratify=stratify)
    return x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test

def object_features(df):
    return list(df.loc[:,df.dtypes=='object'].columns)

def numeric_features(df):
    return list(df.loc[:,(df.dtypes=='int64')|(df.dtypes=='float64')].columns)


def category_features(df,threshold1,threshold2=0):    
    category_features = []
    for each in df.columns:
        if threshold2 < df[each].nunique() < threshold1:
            category_features.append(each)
    return category_features

def check_type(y):
    try:
        condition=y.nunique()
    except:
        condition=len(np.unique(y))
    if condition==2:
        return 'Classification' 
    if 2<condition<10:
        return 'Multi-Class Classification'
    else:
        return 'Regression'

def check_imbalance(y):
    if check_type(y)!='Regression':
        return pd.concat([y.value_counts(),y.value_counts(normalize=True)],axis=1)
    
def check_missing_value(df):
    return any(df.isna().sum()!=0)

def information_table(df):    
    number_instance = df.shape[0]
    number_feature  = df.shape[1]
    
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test= train_test(df,None)
    train_instance = x_train.shape[0]
    test_instance  = x_test.shape[0]
    
    y_type = check_type(y_train)
        
    number_numeric  = len(numeric_features(x_train))
    number_object   = len(object_features(x_train))
    
    missing_value = check_missing_value(x_train)
    
    imbalance = check_imbalance(y_train)
                          
    print('Dataset has ' + str(number_instance) + ' instances and ' + str(number_feature) + ' features.')
    print('After we train test split;')
    print('Training data has ' + str(train_instance) + ' instances and testing data has ' + str(test_instance) + ' instances.')
    print('Class Type is ' + y_type +'.')
    print('Data has ' + str(number_numeric) + ' numeric and ' + str(number_object) + ' object features.')
    if missing_value:
        print('Data has missing value.')
    else:
        print('Data has no missing value.')
    if y_type != 'Regression':
        print('Lets examine imbalance:')
        return imbalance
    else:
        plt.hist(y_train)
        plt.title('Histogram ' + y_train.name)

Preprocess¶

In [13]:
from sklearn import preprocessing
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score

def preprocess(df):
    y=df.iloc[:,-1]
    y_type=check_type(y)
    if y_type=='Regression':
        stratify=None
    else:
        stratify=y
            
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test(df,stratify)
    if check_missing_value(x_train):
        x_train=x_train.fillna(x_train.mean())
        x_test=x_test.fillna(x_test.mean())
    if len(object_features(x_train))>0:
        x_train=pd.get_dummies(x_train)
        x_test=pd.get_dummies(x_test)
    y_type=check_type(y_train)
    if y_type=='Multi-Class Classification':
        encoder = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
        encoder.fit(y_train)
        y_train = encoder.transform(y_train)
        y_test = encoder.transform(y_test)
    return x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test

Models¶

In this section, we initialize all the models that we will use. We will set some candidate values for each model's parameters. Finally, we define some functions which will help us to make some prediction and obtain performance scores in the future.

Penalized Regression Approaches¶

In [15]:
from sklearn.linear_model import ElasticNet
from sklearn.linear_model import SGDClassifier

def penalized_reg(alpha_number=6):
    model=ElasticNet(random_state=0)
    alpha = np.logspace(-2, 3, alpha_number)
    l1_ratio = np.linspace(0,1,5)
     
    tune_params = [{'alpha': alpha,
                   'l1_ratio': l1_ratio}]
    
    return model, tune_params

def penalized_reg_test_score(params,df):
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess(df)    
    model=ElasticNet(random_state=0)
    model.set_params(**params)
    model=model.fit(x_train,y_train)
    pred_train=model.predict(x_train)
    pred_test=model.predict(x_test)
    train_mse=mean_squared_error(y_train,pred_train)*-1
    test_mse=mean_squared_error(y_test,pred_test)*-1
    print('Training Negative Mean Squared Error score is ' + str(train_mse))
    print('Testing Negative Mean Squared Error score is ' + str(test_mse))
    return test_mse

def penalized_class(alpha_number=6):
    model=SGDClassifier(penalty='elasticnet')
    alpha = np.logspace(-2, 3, alpha_number)
    l1_ratio = np.linspace(0,1,5)
     
    tune_params = [{'alpha': alpha,
                   'l1_ratio': l1_ratio}]
    
    return model, tune_params

def penalized_class_test_score(params,df):
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess(df)    
    model=SGDClassifier(random_state=0)
    model.set_params(**params)
    model=model.fit(x_train,y_train)
    pred_train=model.predict(x_train)
    pred_test=model.predict(x_test)
    if check_type(y_train)=='Multi-Class Classification':
        train_f1=f1_score(y_train,pred_train,labels=np.arange(8),average='micro')
        test_f1=f1_score(y_test,pred_test,labels=np.arange(8),average='micro')
        print('Training f1 micro score is ' + str(train_f1))
        print('Testing f1 micro score is ' + str(test_f1))
        return test_f1
    else:
        train_auc=roc_auc_score(y_train,pred_train)
        test_auc=roc_auc_score(y_test,pred_test)
        print('Training ROC AUC score is ' + str(train_auc))
        print('Testing ROC AUC  is ' + str(test_auc))
        return test_auc

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor

def decision_tree():
    model=DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=0)
    
    min_samples_leaf= np.arange(1,7)
    ccp_alpha=np.logspace(-2, 2, 5)
    
    tune_params = [{'ccp_alpha': ccp_alpha,
                    'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf}]
    
    return model, tune_params

def regression_tree():
    model=DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=0)
    
    min_samples_leaf= np.arange(1,7)
    ccp_alpha=np.logspace(-2, 2, 5)
    
    tune_params = [{'ccp_alpha': ccp_alpha,
                    'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf}]
    
    return model, tune_params

def decision_tree_test_score(params,df):
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess(df)    
    model=DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=0)
    model.set_params(**params)
    model=model.fit(x_train,y_train)
    pred_train=model.predict(x_train)
    pred_test=model.predict(x_test)
    if check_type(y_train)=='Multi-Class Classification':
        train_f1=f1_score(y_train,pred_train,average='micro')
        test_f1=f1_score(y_test,pred_test,average='micro')
        print('Training f1 micro score is ' + str(train_f1))
        print('Testing f1 micro score is ' + str(test_f1))
        return test_f1
    else:
        train_auc=roc_auc_score(y_train,pred_train)
        test_auc=roc_auc_score(y_test,pred_test)
        print('Training ROC AUC score is ' + str(train_auc))
        print('Testing ROC AUC  is ' + str(test_auc))
        return test_auc


def regression_tree_test_score(params,df):
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess(df)    
    model=DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=0)
    model.set_params(**params)
    model=model.fit(x_train,y_train)
    pred_train=model.predict(x_train)
    pred_test=model.predict(x_test)
    train_mse=mean_squared_error(y_train,pred_train)*-1
    test_mse=mean_squared_error(y_test,pred_test)*-1
    print('Training Negative Mean Squared Error score is ' + str(train_mse))
    print('Testing Negative Mean Squared Error score is ' + str(test_mse))

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor

def rf_clf(x_train,feature_number=6):
    model=RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=500, min_samples_leaf=5,random_state=0)
    
    max_features=np.round(np.linspace(5,x_train.shape[1],feature_number)).astype(int)
    
    tune_params = [{'max_features': max_features}]
    
    return model, tune_params

def rf_clf_test_score(params,df):
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess(df)    
    model=RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=500, min_samples_leaf=5,random_state=0)
    model.set_params(**params)
    model=model.fit(x_train,y_train)
    pred_train=model.predict(x_train)
    pred_test=model.predict(x_test)
    if check_type(y_train)=='Multi-Class Classification':
        train_f1=f1_score(y_train,pred_train,average='micro')
        test_f1=f1_score(y_test,pred_test,average='micro')
        print('Training f1 micro score is ' + str(train_f1))
        print('Testing f1 micro score is ' + str(test_f1))
        return test_f1
    else:
        train_auc=roc_auc_score(y_train,pred_train)
        test_auc=roc_auc_score(y_test,pred_test)
        print('Training ROC AUC score is ' + str(train_auc))
        print('Testing ROC AUC  is ' + str(test_auc))
        return test_auc


def rf_reg(x_train,feature_number=6):
    model=RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=500, min_samples_leaf=5,random_state=0)
    
    max_features=np.round(np.linspace(5,x_train.shape[1],feature_number)).astype(int)
    
    tune_params = [{'max_features': max_features}]
    
    return model, tune_params
    
def rf_reg_test_score(params,df):
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess(df)    
    model=RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=500, min_samples_leaf=5,random_state=0)
    model.set_params(**params)
    model=model.fit(x_train,y_train)
    pred_train=model.predict(x_train)
    pred_test=model.predict(x_test)
    train_mse=mean_squared_error(y_train,pred_train)*-1
    test_mse=mean_squared_error(y_test,pred_test)*-1
    print('Training Negative Mean Squared Error score is ' + str(train_mse))
    print('Testing Negative Mean Squared Error score is ' + str(test_mse))
    return test_mse

Stochastic Gradient Boosting¶

from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor

def gb_clf(learning_number=4):
    model=GradientBoostingClassifier(min_samples_leaf=10,subsample=0.5,random_state=0)
    
    learning_rate=np.logspace(-4, -1, learning_number)
    n_estimators=[10,20,50,100,150,200]
    max_depth=[2,3,5,10,20]
       
    tune_params = [{'learning_rate': learning_rate,
                    'n_estimators' : n_estimators,
                     'max_depth': max_depth}]
    
    return model, tune_params

def gb_clf_test_score(params,df):
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess(df)    
    model=GradientBoostingClassifier(min_samples_leaf=10,subsample=0.5,random_state=0)
    model.set_params(**params)
    model=model.fit(x_train,y_train)
    pred_train=model.predict(x_train)
    pred_test=model.predict(x_test)
    if check_type(y_train)=='Multi-Class Classification':
        train_f1=f1_score(y_train,pred_train,average='micro')
        test_f1=f1_score(y_test,pred_test,average='micro')
        print('Training f1 micro score is ' + str(train_f1))
        print('Testing f1 micro score is ' + str(test_f1))
        return test_f1
    else:
        train_auc=roc_auc_score(y_train,pred_train)
        test_auc=roc_auc_score(y_test,pred_test)
        print('Training ROC AUC score is ' + str(train_auc))
        print('Testing ROC AUC  is ' + str(test_auc))
        return test_auc


def gb_reg(learning_number=4):
    model=GradientBoostingRegressor(min_samples_leaf=10,subsample=0.5,random_state=0)
    
    learning_rate=np.logspace(-4, -1, learning_number)
    n_estimators=[10,20,50,100,150,200]
    max_depth=[2,3,5,10,20]
       
    tune_params = [{'learning_rate': learning_rate,
                    'n_estimators' : n_estimators,
                     'max_depth': max_depth}]
    
    return model, tune_params

def gb_reg_test_score(params,df):
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess(df)    
    model=GradientBoostingRegressor(min_samples_leaf=10,subsample=0.5,random_state=0)
    model.set_params(**params)
    model=model.fit(x_train,y_train)
    pred_train=model.predict(x_train)
    pred_test=model.predict(x_test)
    train_mse=mean_squared_error(y_train,pred_train)*-1
    test_mse=mean_squared_error(y_test,pred_test)*-1
    print('Training Negative Mean Squared Error score is ' + str(train_mse))
    print('Testing Negative Mean Squared Error score is ' + str(test_mse))
    return test_mse

Parameter Tuning and Cross Validation¶

In this section, we will perform cross validation in order to build a strong model. We will use gridsearchcv method to be able to find good parameters for our model and we interpret our findings. We will follow the steps mentioned below:

  • We will perform gridsearchcv for predefined set of parameters in the previous section.
  • This will resulted with lots of candidate parameter with performance scores.
  • We won't select parameters with the highest score,
  • Instead we will groupby each parameter with respect to its values and calculate the mean of the performance score (training and validation) for the grouped values
  • This way we will be able to discover the real relationship between the parameters.
  • We will select an arbitrary parameters.
  • Then we will fit the candidate and measure performance score on testing data.
  • We plot everything in a graph. (cross validation scores of each parameter group on training, validation data and performance of testing data)
  • Finally we will readjust the candidate solution to optimal one.

Lets define some functions:

In [38]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

def cross_validate(x_train,y_train,model,tune_params,cv):
    y_type = check_type(y_train)
    if y_type == 'Regression':
        cross_validate = GridSearchCV(model,tune_params,scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',cv=cv,return_train_score=True,n_jobs=-2)
        cross_validate_fit=cross_validate.fit(x_train,y_train)
    elif y_type == 'Classification':
        cross_validate = GridSearchCV(model,tune_params,scoring='roc_auc',cv=cv,return_train_score=True,n_jobs=-2)
        cross_validate_fit=cross_validate.fit(x_train,y_train)
    else:
        cross_validate = GridSearchCV(model,tune_params,scoring='f1_micro',cv=cv,return_train_score=True,n_jobs=-2)
        cross_validate_fit=cross_validate.fit(x_train,y_train)
    return cross_validate_fit.cv_results_


def perform_cv(dic,cv):
    combined_dict={}
    
    for k,v in dic.items():
        new_dict={}
        x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess(v)
        
        y_type = check_type(y_train)
        if y_type != 'Regression':
            model,tune_params= penalized_class()
            name = str(model).split('(')[0]
            new_dict.update({name:cross_validate(x_train,y_train,model,tune_params,cv)})

            
            model,tune_params= decision_tree()
            name = str(model).split('(')[0]
            new_dict.update({name:cross_validate(x_train,y_train,model,tune_params,cv)})

            model,tune_params=rf_clf(x_train)
            name = str(model).split('(')[0]
            new_dict.update({name:cross_validate(x_train,y_train,model,tune_params,cv)})

            model,tune_params=gb_clf()
            name = str(model).split('(')[0]
            new_dict.update({name:cross_validate(x_train,y_train,model,tune_params,cv)})

        else:
            model,tune_params= penalized_reg()
            name = str(model).split('(')[0]
            new_dict.update({name:cross_validate(x_train,y_train,model,tune_params,cv)})

            
            model,tune_params= regression_tree()
            name = str(model).split('(')[0]
            new_dict.update({name:cross_validate(x_train,y_train,model,tune_params,cv)})

            model,tune_params=rf_reg(x_train)
            name = str(model).split('(')[0]
            new_dict.update({name:cross_validate(x_train,y_train,model,tune_params,cv)})

            model,tune_params=gb_reg()
            name = str(model).split('(')[0]
            new_dict.update({name:cross_validate(x_train,y_train,model,tune_params,cv)})

        combined_dict.update({k:new_dict})
    return combined_dict


combined_dict=perform_cv(dic,5)
In [39]:
def filter_columns(df,name):
    return [col for col in df if col.startswith(name)]

def check_lenght(list1):
    return len(list1)

def groupby_wrt_param(combined_dict):
    dic1={}
    for k1,v1 in combined_dict.items():
        dic2={}
        for k2, v2, in v1.items():
            list1=filter_columns(v2,'param_')
            len_list1=check_lenght(list1)
            list1.append('mean_test_score')
            list1.append('mean_train_score')
            df=pd.DataFrame.from_dict(v2)[list1]
            if len_list1==1:
                grouped=df.groupby([df[list1[0]]]).agg({'mean_test_score':'mean','mean_train_score':'mean'})
                dic2.update({k2:[grouped]})
        
            elif len_list1==2:
                grouped1=df.groupby([df[list1[0]]]).agg({'mean_test_score':'mean','mean_train_score':'mean'})
                grouped2=df.groupby([df[list1[1]]]).agg({'mean_test_score':'mean','mean_train_score':'mean'})
                dic2.update({k2:[grouped1,grouped2]})
        
            elif len_list1==3:
                grouped1=df.groupby([df[list1[0]]]).agg({'mean_test_score':'mean','mean_train_score':'mean'})
                grouped2=df.groupby([df[list1[1]]]).agg({'mean_test_score':'mean','mean_train_score':'mean'})
                grouped3=df.groupby([df[list1[2]]]).agg({'mean_test_score':'mean','mean_train_score':'mean'})
                dic2.update({k2:[grouped1,grouped2,grouped3]})
        dic1.update({k1:dic2})    
    return dic1
    
grouped = groupby_wrt_param(combined_dict)

def get_dataset(grouped,dataset_name):
    return grouped[dataset_name]

def get_data(grouped,dataset_name,model_name):
    dic=get_dataset(grouped,dataset_name)
    return dic[model_name]

def cv_plot(test_score,list1,title): #this function enables us to plot cv_scores wrt parameters we selected
    
    c1='orange'
    c2='grey'
    c3='navy'  
    
    
    fig, host = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,5)) # (width, height) in inches
    
    fig.suptitle(title, y=1.05)
   
    if len(list1)==1:
        p1, = host.plot(list1[0]['mean_test_score'],list1[0].index.values,color=c1, label='validation '+list1[0].index.name)
        p1, = host.plot(list1[0]['mean_train_score'],list1[0].index.values,color=c1, linestyle='dashed', marker='+',label='train '+list1[0].index.name)
    
        host.set_xlabel("Performance")
        host.set_ylabel(list1[0].index.name)
            
    if len(list1)==2:
        
        par1 = host.twinx()
        
        p1, = host.semilogy(list1[0]['mean_test_score'],list1[0].index.values,color=c1, label='validation '+list1[0].index.name)
        p1, = host.semilogy(list1[0]['mean_train_score'],list1[0].index.values,color=c1, linestyle='dashed', marker='+',label='train '+list1[0].index.name)

        p2, = par1.plot(list1[1]['mean_test_score'],list1[1].index.values,color=c2, label='validation '+list1[1].index.name)
        p2, = par1.plot(list1[1]['mean_train_score'],list1[1].index.values,color=c2, linestyle='dashed', marker='+',label='train '+list1[1].index.name)

        host.set_xlabel("Performance")
        host.set_ylabel(list1[0].index.name)
        par1.set_ylabel(list1[1].index.name)        
        
    if len(list1)==3:
        
        par1 = host.twinx()
        par2 = host.twinx()
                
        p1, = host.plot(list1[0]['mean_test_score'],list1[0].index.values,color=c1, label='validation '+list1[0].index.name)
        p1, = host.plot(list1[0]['mean_train_score'],list1[0].index.values,color=c1, linestyle='dashed', marker='+', label='train '+list1[0].index.name)

        p2, = par1.plot(list1[1]['mean_test_score'],list1[1].index.values,color=c2, label='validation '+list1[1].index.name)
        p2, = par1.plot(list1[1]['mean_train_score'],list1[1].index.values,color=c2, linestyle='dashed', marker='+', label='train '+list1[1].index.name)
        
        p3, = par2.plot(list1[2]['mean_test_score'],list1[2].index.values,color=c3,  label='validation '+list1[2].index.name)
        p3, = par2.plot(list1[2]['mean_train_score'],list1[2].index.values,color=c3, linestyle='dashed', marker='+', label='train '+list1[2].index.name)
        
        host.set_xlabel("Performance")
        host.set_ylabel(list1[0].index.name)
        par1.set_ylabel(list1[1].index.name)
        par2.set_ylabel(list1[2].index.name)

        par2.spines['right'].set_position(('outward', 60))
        
    host.axvline(test_score, color='red', linestyle='dotted', label='test score')
    plt.grid()
    fig.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc=2)        
    fig.tight_layout()

There are four options:

  • Performing good
  • Overfitted
  • Underfitted
  • Not performing good

If we briefly explain these option:

If our training data give good scores but the test data give much worse scores compare to training data, it means that model overfitted to data. In other words, the model learning too specific pattern for the given data we cannot generalize it to other data.

If both training and test data give bad results, this means that either the model is underfitted or the model is not suitable for the given data. To solve the underfitting issue we can further tune the model's parameters. For instance max iteration number for elasticnet and sgdclassifier.

Our validation result and test result behave similarly, mostly because we didn't take best validation result, instead we obtained the candidate solution by looking at the means.

The ranking of the models for each dataset is given below;

In [155]:
def ranking(all_performance_dict,dataset,criteria):
    df=pd.DataFrame.from_dict(all_performance_dict[dataset],orient='index') 
    df.columns=[criteria]
    df.sort_values([criteria],ascending=False,inplace=True)
    df['Rank']=[1,2,3,4]
    return df
